{
  "text": "Existing state-of-the-art works try to bring together some aspects of the Liquid Software principals (e.g. fluidity), using different techniques such as interface mismatches [CITATION_1] , middleware, synchronization [CITATION_2] , cross-device [CITATION_3] , among others. However, none of these approaches considers both multi-(device/OS) issues while allowing devices switching. In addition, these approaches rely on Server-side synchronization and independent devices authentication to ensure web services data-flow migration through devices. The CUBE model is intended to address this challenge based on USER-SIDE synchronization. II. SYSTEM MODEL We briefly describe here the CUBE model principles which is a foundation of our contribution in order to deal with connected multi-devices owned by the same user. From the portion 100, the content management system 101 will interact on two fronts, user's and services sides. First, at 100, a device is specified as the first one. Its choice is made from the available devices owned by the same user. Then, at 107, the CUBE will be able to receive and respond to different types of requests made by the 100. Meanwhile, services are synchronized at API 106.",
  "citation_candidates": [
    "11465157",
    "35247792",
